<h3>Visit 1: Reading and Reflection</h3>
<p class="border"><img alt="Youg adults painting the side of a building" height="113" src="Images/Admin_Offices/Online Learning/Speaking Partners/images/English1.png" style="border: 1px solid black;" width="240" /></p>
<p><a href="Documents/Admin_Offices/Online Learning/Online Instruction/Speaking Partner ENG/GS 120L Lesson 10.pdf">GS 120L Lesson 10 PDF</a></p>
<p>Today&rsquo;s assignment to discuss: <strong>Your feelings about reading.</strong></p>
<p>Discuss with your Speaking Partner the following:</p>
<p>1. Describe what the people are doing in each of the pictures. <br /><img height="209" src="Images/Admin_Offices/Online%20Learning/Speaking%20Partners/images/SPWeek10--StudentStudySpori(0).jpg" style="border: none;" width="250" />&nbsp;<img height="177" src="Images/Admin_Offices/Online%20Learning/Speaking%20Partners/images/SPWeek10--navyreadchildren.jpg" style="border: none;" width="270" /><br />2. Do you like to read?</p>
<ul>
<li>If you answered &ldquo;yes&rdquo; to the above question, where did you develop your love of reading?</li>
<li>If you answered &ldquo;no&rdquo; to the above question, how do you think you can develop a love of reading?</li>
</ul>
<p>3. What type of books or other things do you read?</p>
<ul></ul>
<h3>Visit 2: Reading Good Books</h3>
<p class="border"><img alt="Young man praying with hands clasped" height="113" src="Images/Admin_Offices/Online Learning/Speaking Partners/images/English10.png" style="border: 1px solid black;" width="240" /></p>
<p>Read the following words of President Gordon B. Hinckley to your Speaking Partner. Read one time through and discuss pronunciation, unfamiliar phrases, or vocabulary words. Read another time through and discuss the importance of reading good books.</p>
<table border="1" style="border-color: #000000; border-width: 1px; width: 900px;">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>
<p>The Hinckley family lived in Salt Lake City in a home with a very large library. &ldquo;That was a great place to go to read and study,&rdquo; recalled President Hinckley. &ldquo;Both of my parents were well educated and had a great love for learning. We had more than a thousand books in our library, and my mother read to us when we were children.&hellip;</p>
<p>&ldquo;We ought to strive to learn and to read good books. It&rsquo;s fine to watch some television, but we don&rsquo;t need to watch too much of it. We&rsquo;d do better to spend more time reading good books.&rdquo;</p>
<p>(by Janet Peterson, &ldquo;Friend to Friend,&rdquo;&nbsp;<em>Friend</em>, February 1987)</p>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>Questions:</p>
<ol>
<li>Describe President Hinckley&rsquo;s home and how they felt about reading.</li>
<li>What is the difference between watching TV and reading a book?</li>
<li>Where can you go to find good books? Do you have a library near you?</li>
</ol>
